		<Backstory>Ayman's tale is one of survival through fortune in the face of overwhelming odds.  As a youngling, he was abandoned on the ravaged plains when his clan, on the brink of starvation, determined that they could not feed the entire group.  He was found by a passing human traveller who took pity on him and fostered him until his adolescence.  At that time, however, his foster family's homestead was attacked by wildings and burned while he was out hunting small game; he was the only survivor.  Upon returning to the scene of destruction, Ayman quickly picked up what he could salvage from the rubble, and determined to revenge himself on the wildings.  He galloped in a fury after their warband and caught up to them as they neared their village.  Perhaps it was the novelty of the sight of the lone charging centaur youth, or perhaps they were merely unwary in the exuberance of their victorious raid, but none stopped him as he galloped into their midst and trampled down the leader of the warband, killing him.  At this point, he collapsed, exhausted.  The wildings did not slay Ayman, though, as their custom dictated that one who defeats the chieftain in combat should be the new chieftan.  After he regained his composure and breath, he warily determined that the rest of the wildings were submitting to him.  His fury spent, and not having a life to return to, he remained with them and learned their ways, especially those of their shaman, a wizened crone of peculiar humor and an insatiable appetite for mushrooms.  He would frequently roam the wildlands with the old shaman on his back cracking jokes, ever in search of the best spots for the elusive fungus. After two years' time, he left the wildings to undertake a shamanic vision quest and never returned.  He will not speak of what she saw or heard, but Ayman claims that he gained great mystic understanding during the journey.  	

Sometime after his vision quest, Ayman ended up wandering near the edges of one of the few remaining patches of forest.  Unaccustomed to such sights, he entered the forest where he encountered the sight of an elf child being attacked by a giant spider.  Ayman rushed to help the child, but while he successfully slew the spider, he was bitten in the process and fell into a deep coma.  While he was unconscious, the elf child raced to her village and returned with her elders, who were able to transport Ayman back to their village and nurse him back to health.  In gratitude, the elves invited Ayman to stay with them, which he did for a season, and then granted him the best bow in their village as a token of esteem when he left.

Since that time, Ayman has moved about, living with a variety of peoples, and has developed very tolerant and expansive views as a consequence.  He's extraordinarily good at mediating disputes, having a wealth of background insight to draw from.  If he has any faults or biases, it is a dislike for his own people and their misogynistic tendencies.</Backstory>

